前的事情了。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以这很有趣，因为有一段时间，我们所说的耶鲁模型，真正是大卫·斯文森的天才，是他在替代品还很小的时候就很早就采用了，它们大多表现出色，有很多阿尔法一代，这不是一个可以钓鱼的大池塘，而耶鲁大学的模型却表现得非常出色。捐赠基金的驱动因素是什么？如果不是表现不佳，那么，肯定比我们在 80 年代、90 年代和 2000 年代初看到的表现更差。</p><p> SEIDES：是的，我的意思是，我对你所说的唯一警告是我不确定你是否正确测量了它，性能更差。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：哦不，情况更糟。</p><p> SEIDES：更低。更低了。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：好的，这很公平。</p><p> SEIDES：但市场回报——</p><p> RITHOLTZ：过去十年，2010年到2020年，我们是什么？ 14、一年15%？</p><p> SEIDES：如果标准普尔指数是你的基准，那么它不适用于这些资本池。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：他们的基准应该是什么？顺便说一句，这是一个非常公平的观点。您是全球投资者。也许标准普尔并不是最好的选择。</p><p>赛德斯：是的，没错。我的意思是，大卫·斯文森 (David Swensen) 的早期创新信念之一是，如果你管理的资本池实际上是一个永久的时间范围。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：无限，对吧？</p><p> SEIDES：你想要深思熟虑的多元化。因此，如果您从标准普尔 500 指数开始，或者在本例中是股票和债券，那么您只有两种资产类别，对吧。问题是，如果你能找到其他投资领域，能够产生你的负债流所需的回报类型，多元化就成为免费午餐。</p><p>因此，这些资金池的正确基准必须看起来有点像他们投资的基础资产。</p><p>里索兹：很公平。那么你用什么作为基准呢？现在请记住，让我们以大卫投资的项目为例。当然有股票和债券，但也有房地产。在人们还不知道之前就已经有了商品。等等，木头？我们为什么投资木材？然后是风险投资、私人信贷和对冲基金。</p><p>那么，如何为看起来与 60/40 分配完全不同的分配创建基准呢？</p><p> SEIDES：嗯，你必须考虑一下你想要衡量的是什么。因此，正如您所说，一个合理的基准可能是 60/40 或 70/30。这是一个非常容易创建的投资组合。可以肯定的是，在过去的 10 年、15 年里，它是很难被击败的。</p><p>从较长一段时间来看，也许不会那么多。</p><p>如果您查看耶鲁大学投资的资产类型，您可以为每个池创建一个基准。这允许您做两件事。一般来说，它可以让您了解整个投资组合的合理贝塔值是多少。它允许你做的另一件事是衡量你选择在每个领域和整个袖子上都表现出色的经理的能力。</p><p>所以你可以想象在房地产领域，有一个你可以使用的净租赁房地产指数。您也可以使用房地产投资信托基金指数，尽管它在私人市场上有所不同。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> SEIDES：您可以使用风险投资和私募股权方面的纯粹基准，然后您可以将各个资产类别的基准进行汇总，以获得整个池的基准。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：真的很有趣。所以耶鲁模式全盛时期以来发生了两个问题，一是大家都在模仿耶鲁模式。所以第一个问题是，这是否会给想要遵循耶鲁模式的分配者带来挑战？它不再是，“嘿，我自己拥有了整个领域。我还有 500 个其他捐赠基金、基金会和机构试图参与进来——试图在这个池塘里钓鱼。”</p><p> SEIDES：是的，确实如此。我认为，当你思考耶鲁模型时，它有助于理解大卫的想法，而不是你给耶鲁模型贴上的标签及其含义。</p><p>大卫的才华之一是他从第一原则开始做一切事情。有什么意义呢？您对世界和投资有什么信念？那么你如何以严格的纪律来应用它呢？</p><p>他在他的书中写到了这一点，人们看到后会说：“哦，我可以复制它。”但大多数人都很难拥有自己的信念，并在执行方面遇到困难时坚持自己的信念。</p><p>大卫拥有的另一点无人能真正复制的是对持续改进的坚定信念和令人难以置信的远见，既能看到大机会，就像你可以想象很久以前的对冲基金一样，也能看到小机会。因此，他在 35、40 年前就先于其他人考虑了收费问题，以及何时可以对此采取行动。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：就是他和杰克·博格尔，仅此而已。</p><p>赛德斯：是的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：考虑费用。这样做的缺点是，我要借用吉姆·查诺斯的话，他谈到 Kynikos Associates 著名的卖空者时说，“在 80 年代，有 500 家对冲基金。他们都产生了阿尔法。现在有 11,000 家对冲基金，其中 500 家正在创造阿尔法收益。”所以另一个挑战是如何从11,000个对冲基金和10,000个风险基金以及天知道有多少私募股权基金和私募信贷基金中进行选择，使得配置内的选择似乎变得更加困难，更多复杂，即使你找到了你真正喜欢的基金经理，你现在也正在与其他有限合伙人竞争将你的十亿美元投入那里。</p><p> SEIDES：是的，这是绝对正确的，根据资产类别，有不同的镜头组。但仅以多头空头股权投资为例，您要问的第一个问题是，这是您想要的地方吗？</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> SEIDES：因为这是一场更加艰难的比赛，特别是在空头方面比以前增加了价值。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：做空一直很困难。有这样一个神话：人们先建立空头头寸，然后谈论它，然后数钱。这比那要困难得多。</p><p>赛德斯：是的。所以我认为在任何资产类别中选择管理者都需要这两点。那么我们回到大卫的首要原则，你认为哪种类型的经理应该表现出色？有些人认为，与那些比其他人更了解自己业务的人进行基本自由裁量投资是正确的做法。</p><p>还有其他人认为，“不，你需要像 Citadel 或 Millennium 那样规模庞大、系统化。”没有对错之分，但您必须遵循自己的一套信念，以确保您认为对您的泳池有用。</p><p>另一方面，比如你提到的风险投资，访问确实很重要。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> SEIDES：这就是你可以看到耶鲁大学并说他们在 30 年前就拥有先发优势的地方。他们已经是顶级风险投资经理，不从任何人那里拿钱。有很多投资者说，我在播客上说，“如果我们无法进入那些顶级风险投资，”你就没有风险投资的分配，你有一群经理。你拿走你能得到的东西，但你不会超出你认为是最顶层的范围，因为该资产类别的分散回报非常广泛，而你只想进入，比如说，顶级核心顶层。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以我们将回到您稍后提到的播客内容，因为我对此很感兴趣。但我喜欢先发优势的想法。</p><p>当你想到耶鲁模型时，当斯文森第一次分配给其他资产类型、商品、土地、替代品时，那是狂野的西部。门是敞开的。作为这些领域的先驱，他有多大优势？老笑话是：“是啊，是啊，第二只老鼠得到了奶酪。”在这种情况下，看起来第一只老鼠得到了奶酪。</p><p> SEIDES：是的，是在桶里射鱼。</p><p>里索兹：真的吗？</p><p> SEIDES：当我在耶鲁大学工作时，游戏中最困难的部分是了解游戏的玩法，知道去哪里访问它，然后最重要的是，获得董事会的批准让你这样做。</p><p>举一些例子，我于 92 年加入耶鲁大学，大卫于 85 年加入耶鲁大学。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> SEIDES：他们到达那里时进行了一些风险投资。这并不完整，但他们喜欢它。他们很快就意识到了这一点的潜力。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：谁，董事会？</p><p> SEIDES：不，耶鲁大学，David 和 Dean Takashi，耶鲁大学的团队。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：但是监督和治理做到了吗？</p><p> SEIDES：他们已经就位了。他们真的做到了。</p><p>里索兹：好的。</p><p> SEIDES：这是耶鲁大学成功的一个重要方面。</p><p>里索兹：毫无疑问。</p><p> SEIDES：治理的成功。所以他们然后有时间去硅谷与人们会面，看看十多年来谁是好人，谁不是，提出问题并犯错误。这是一个巨大的先发优势。</p><p>当我 92 年到达那里时，他们已经拥有了很棒的风险投资组合，几乎没有其他人了解风险投资是什么。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：93 年、94 年、95 年才刚刚开始兴起，到 90 年代末，每个人都蜂拥而至。如果你是十年前的人，请谈谈先行者。哦，我的天啊。</p><p> SEIDES：对冲基金也是如此。为了给您讲一个有趣的故事，我们在 2002 年推出了 Protégé Partners。在 92 年到 02 年这段时间里，就回报而言，您确实经历了对冲基金的黄金时代。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：在金融危机爆发前的一两年里，对冲基金把它压垮了。或者至少在顶部，选择一个数字，30%、40%。少、20%、30%？</p><p> SEIDES：我知道当时资产管理领域的首要工作是管理富达麦哲伦。没有理由认为人们会通过经营对冲基金赚到数十亿美元。这是一个精品行业。我曾经说过，那些经营对冲基金的人早上在床的另一边醒来，觉得自己不得不做空，因为事情出了问题。</p><p>里索兹：（笑）</p><p> SEIDES：因此，当我们推出 Protégé 时，我们对对冲基金进行了分类，并表示我们不会投资大型基金。 2002 年，最大的对冲基金的资产规模超过 10 亿美元。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>赛德斯：然后我开始联系我在耶鲁大学期间认识的一些经理，其中一位对我说：“我们已经关门了。我们有一个等候名单。”我说：“那是什么？”他说：“我不知道。”但突然间，人们说：“你为什么不开始等待名单呢？”</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我们已经达到了极限，仅此而已。</p><p> SEIDES：2002 年之前，无论你认为最好的对冲基金是谁，都不存在能力问题。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：随后，有一些学术研究暗示，我不想说发现了，但强烈暗示阿尔法的很大一部分来自新兴管理者，而且不是大部分。</p><p> SEIDES：这就是我们在 Protege 开展业务的前提。我想告诉你，虽然学术研究确实如此，但它都存在严重缺陷。所有这些。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：嗯，这里面有一点事后偏见，对吧？</p><p> SEIDES：存在事后偏见。您真正想要衡量的经理的数据不包含在其中。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这都是自我报告的，对吧？</p><p> SEIDES：然后我从未见过有研究表明大型管理者的资产超过 5000 万美元。</p><p>里索尔兹：什么？</p><p> SEIDES：所以你看一下这些研究，他们说小规模的研究少于 500 万。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：一百万还是十亿？我们正在谈论的是——听起来像是一个错字。因为如果你看看 Millennium、Citadel、Oak Tree 和 AQR，它们刚刚度过了美妙的一年，还有 Bridgewater，我们谈论的是 50、100、1500 亿美元。这些都是巨大的资本池。</p><p> SEIDES：问题是进行研究的学者无法获得重要基金的绩效数据。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> SEIDES：它们都不是资产加权的。因此，这些研究虽然是真实的，虽然它们在思考过程中似乎具有智力活力，但它们实际上并不是基于投资市场现实世界中的任何内容。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以所有这些都提出了一个显而易见的问题。沃伦·巴菲特是对的吗？大多数人投资指数基金是否比投资主动型基金经理更好，无论是共同基金还是高费用对冲基金？</p><p> SEIDES：约翰是的，我当时就说过，赌注始于 2007 年，现在我说，进入市场并投资对冲基金完全是苹果和橘子的关系。因此，对于应税投资者来说，对冲基金通常不具有税收效率。当你查看投资的资产时，即对冲基金的 3 万亿美元，我猜想其中 90% 以上都投资于不纳税的机构。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：David So 基金会、捐赠基金。</p><p> SEIDES: So as an individual, it probably doesn&#39;t make sense, generally speaking.</p><p> As an institution, it has a very different risk return profile that when done well, fits in really well with the diversified portfolio that we&#39;ve talked about earlier.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: You have to tell us, where did the idea come from? How did you reach out to Buffett? And what was his response?</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah. Well, and you have to go back. This is the summer of 2007.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: 2007. So, let me set the table a little bit. You had the run up in the dot coms to 2000. I have a vivid recollection of people saying, “Ah, Buffett&#39;s old. He&#39;s lost his touch,” right? Then everything implodes and again, Buffett is outperforming for a while. Post October lows in &#39;02, March double bottom &#39;03, the invasion of Iraq. By the time you get to &#39;07, market&#39;s up 80, 90% from the lows and housing is just about peaking and things are starting to come apart around then. By &#39;07, it&#39;s pretty clear that the housing bears are going to be right.</p><p> SEIDES: That&#39;s right. So I had seen that Warren had made a comment to a bunch of students. A year or two before that, he had written about fees, the had rocks and the got rocks. And I guess he had made some throwaway comment that hedge funds could never beat the market. A student asked him about it and his response was, “Well, no one&#39;s taken me up on it, so I must be right.”</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Meaning no one&#39;s taken me up on his statement or did he lay out a challenge?</p><p> SEIDES: I&#39;m not quite sure because I didn&#39;t hear what he originally said, but it came off as it was a form of a challenge. And at the time, I was managing Protege Partners as a hedge fund of funds. We were short subprime mortgages with John Paulson.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: You were crushing it. Let me say what your compliance wouldn&#39;t allow you to say. You guys were killing it in the mid 2000s.</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah, we had a great run. And I read a statement and my thought was, “Look, he&#39;s Warren Buffett, but he just made a really bad bet.”</p><p> RITHOLTZ: (LAUGH)</p><p> SEIDES: Because for all the reasons you just said, the S&amp;P was trading at all-time highs.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> SEIDES: Let&#39;s keep in mind interest rates were normalized then. And —</p><p> RITHOLTZ: What? They had just started going up.</p><p> SEIDES: Well, rates, short-term rates were four or five, six percent. I don&#39;t remember the number. Okay, so reasonable, right?是的。 And I looked at that and said, “Well, you wouldn&#39;t want to bet on the market over 10 years starting at that point in time.” Meanwhile, hedge funds had been cranking along generating market-like returns with a lot less volatility. And so I wrote him a one page letter.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Email or hard copy?</p><p> SEIDES: I didn&#39;t have his email. So I sent it snail mail. And he sent back through his assistant a PDF with a little chicken scratch response. And I made the letter, I actually put the letter in my first book to describe how you get somebody&#39;s attention. And he said, “Well, it has to be this and that “and it has to be collateralized with a letter of credit.” And I was like, “What?” And so I sent him another one.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Specifically the bet, he wanted cash upfront, letter of credit.</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah, it was unclear.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: But he didn&#39;t want anybody just sort of fooling around. He wanted serious.</p><p> SEIDES: Correct. It felt a little dismissive, so I sent him another one. I said, “Okay, fine.”</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Whatever you say, I&#39;m in.</p><p> SEIDES: Whatever you say, let&#39;s do it. And then it–</p><p> RITHOLTZ: He&#39;s Warren Buffett. Why are you going to argue with him about it, right? What are the terms? Great, I&#39;m in.</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah, it started a back and forth series of letters, it was all written out, that was hysterical.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: By the way, I just picture this as a sort of a civil war soldier writing home, dearest Martha, I am considering, like in the 2000s, you guys were sending letters back and forth.</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah, that&#39;s right. And it got to the point where there was the potential to do this nonprofit, like charitable bet.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: By the way, I don&#39;t even have to ask, but I&#39;m going to ask, you have all these letters saved, framed somewhere, like, please tell me you kept everything.</p><p> SEIDES: It&#39;s in a PDF.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Okay. But I mean the originals, just the original. So three, four, five times, how many times back and forth?</p><p> SEIDES: Something like that. I don&#39;t remember the exact amount. And I had originally said, hey, let&#39;s bet dinner at Gorat&#39;s, his favorite place, maybe $100,000, your annual salary, all that kind of stuff.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Oh no, he wants to step it up.</p><p> SEIDES: He said that his estate planners would be, thought he was nuts anyway for doing something so small, but yeah. So I went and talked to my partners at Protégé, Scott Bessent, who now runs a macro hedge fund, ran Soros after for a year, my original partner passed away a couple years ago, and said, “Hey, by the way, “I&#39;ve been corresponding with Warren about this.” Like, what? And Scott read the letters, and he said, “I&#39;ll never forget this.” He said, “Huh, it looks like Warren recognizes “he&#39;s the patsy at the poker table, but he has the most chips.”</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> SEIDES: Because every time I&#39;d say, okay, let&#39;s do it this way, there was something back that said, well, it has to be like this. And it got to the point where he said, okay, do we want to do this or not? And then it&#39;s actually hard to make a legal bet. It&#39;s probably easier now, right? Some betting is a legalist, but then it wasn&#39;t. And he found, through his lawyer, a foundation called the Long Bets Foundation.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Sure, they&#39;ve been around for a long time.</p><p> SEIDES: That allows you to make charitable bets based on long-term educational beliefs. And so that&#39;s what we did. And we made it for a million dollars. We split the amount and bought a zero coupon bond of the present value upfront. So back in 2007.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So 10 years in advance with a four or five, so what, it was like 400,000?</p><p> SEIDES: It was 650, so we just put in 325 or something.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Oh, really?</p><p> SEIDES: And then the money would go to the winner&#39;s charity at the end of 10 years.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: That&#39;s a very reasonable bet. That&#39;s a very honorable bet because it&#39;s not a matter of taking money from one person or another. Both people are kicking money in. So technically, and that&#39;s probably why it was legal, there&#39;s no gambling involved.</p><p> SEIDES: And I&#39;ll tell you a story that&#39;s fun about the communication 