ht happen. Tell us a little bit about how you came to that and while being stuck in the moment is so problematic for long-term returns.</p><p> SEIDES: Well, if you look at what happened with SVB, a mismanagement of the balance sheet. So you go back a couple of years and you could say, “Well, what return is available buying a treasury?” And it turned out, if you looked at the market at that time, it was, I&#39;ll call it 1%, five-year treasury or 10-year treasury. So you say, “Well, we need to invest. We are deposits cost less than that. We&#39;re going to earn a spread, so we&#39;re going to invest at 1%.”</p><p> The problem with that, of course, is that if you said, “What return is available” let&#39;s say over the next 10 years and it was 1%, it turns out you were wrong because the right thing to do was to sit on cash and wait till rates moved to 5%.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Especially when the Fed said, “We&#39;re taking rates up aggressively post late &#39;21, early &#39;22.” It wasn&#39;t that they didn&#39;t communicate that.</p><p> SEIDES: Correct. So if you look at that over a longer period of time and say, “Well, my opportunity set isn&#39;t just what&#39;s available today. It&#39;s what&#39;s available today and might be available tomorrow and I can forego a tiny bit of return in the near term, turn a much higher return at some unknowable time in the future.” That could have saved SVB. It could have saved First Republic.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So hold the duration risk aside with those two, but just for an investor in treasuries, I know you&#39;ve done the math before. If you&#39;re giving up that 1% big fat yield in 2019, 2021, let&#39;s say you give up three years of 1% and get zero, how does the math work over the subsequent couple of years? How would you have done?</p><p> SEIDES: Well, you&#39;ve done a lot better, right? So even take a five-year period. You go one, one, one, one, one, or zero, zero, zero, five, five.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Way ahead.</p><p> SEIDES: You g